    "analysis": "The Executor previously loaded the four telemetry files and produced a compact summary. From that summary: metric.csv contains 9,251 rows spanning 2024-01-23 04:36:00 to 2024-01-23 05:00:00 UTC and has KPI names including cpu, mem, socket, diskio, workload, latency-50, latency-90, and error. trace.csv and log.csv also contain many rows covering roughly the same time range. error_logs.csv is empty. The incident window (2024-01-23 04:33:01 to 2024-01-23 05:03:01 UTC) overlaps with the available telemetry, though metric/trace/log data start at 04:36:00. Next we must follow the prescribed workflow: compute global thresholds per component-KPI using the full available series (before filtering), then filter those series to the incident window and detect anomalies. Per the rules, we should restrict metric analysis to the candidate root-cause services only: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. We'll compute both high-side (>=P95) and low-side (<=P5) anomalies because some KPIs (e.g., workload/traffic) can show failures as drops. We need compact aggregated outputs (counts, earliest timestamps, extremes) and must not return full time series. No code shown here; this is a description of what was done and what to do next.",
